@Sam McNamara I also noticed the color chosen to represent each one. The red graph shows a worst-case scenario and is colored accordingly. 
You also mentioned that you were questioning if the graph is exaggerated or not. Honestly, I do not think it is. If we look at the situation in New York, their medical capabilities have already been overrun with coronavirus patients and they are having to choose who gets a ventilator and who does not. Essentially, the doctors have the power of who lives and who dies in their hands and there is nothing they can do to save everyone. 
The takeaway that I get from this graph as well as what is happening in New York is that the American people must save themselves. There is only so much our government can do. We need to buckle down, take this seriously, and stay home. The title of this graph should be "Why Social Distancing Works" to emphasize that there is something we can do to stop the crisis and feel a little less helpless.

@Anna Kilpatrick, You raise a good question.  How would our Healthcare system deal with those who contract the Covid-19 virus once our Healthcare system has already reached the maximum amount of patients that they can treat safely?  The sad answer to your question has been happening in Italy over the past few weeks.  Due to the unsuspected rapid increase of Covid-19 cases in Italy, they were not prepared for the effects of the virus.  The Italian hospitals do not have near enough resources to cure patients and thousands have died due to the sheer lack of resources.  They do not have an adequate amount of ventilators to keep patients alive and they have to choose which patient will live and which will die.  It is truly awful.  

Three days ago 512 italians died due to Covid-19.  Just two days ago, over 700 Italians died from Covid-19.  That number is still increasing as 743 died yesterday.  The Italian government is becoming the perfect example of how to not treat the Covid-19 outbreak by not preparing themselves.  The virus could have done so much less damage to their country if the government had begun preparing for its imminent arrival months ago.  

Without protective measures we would all die.  Stay inside and wash your hands!

@Taryn Connolly I absolutely agree with you. We must practice taking protective measures if we want to contain this virus and stop its spreading as soon as possible. By allowing it to exceed the healthcare system capacity, I fear the cases won't ever go back down, and we would witness another "black death." 

I don't think determining when the data was taken is necessary important for the chart. The chart is all theoretical, and so it is predicating would could happen. Although it is important to use the most up to date data, this is just a predication, and we should use it as a part of making an overall decision. 

I also noticed that there is a quite a lot missing from the chart. What scale factors are being used, where was the data compiled, and what exactly are protective measures? These questions are important for interpreting and understanding the data in its entirety, and without them many of us could be left confused or, more dangerously, inaccurately reading what the chart is saying. Some could assume that by not taking any protective measures, the number of cases will go back down to zero, so they will continue to live their lives as normal. This is not advisable by anyone in the scientific community, and if people start to think that's it fine to not practice any safety measures, the number of cases, and deaths, could rise astronomically.

